00:07:36.760 --> 00:07:38.300
the 20th century.

00:07:38.300 --> 00:07:42.640
And what he won the Nobel
Prize for-- with others--

00:07:42.640 --> 00:07:46.040
was the recognition that, of
course, at a fundamental level,

00:07:46.040 --> 00:07:47.800
the world is quantum mechanical.

00:07:47.800 --> 00:07:50.020
And if we want to have a
theory of electromagnetism,

00:07:50.020 --> 00:07:52.540
we need to put it in accord
with quantum mechanics.

00:07:52.540 --> 00:07:55.054
And the theory they developed
called quantum electrodynamics

00:07:55.054 --> 00:07:57.220
is a theory that merges
electromagnetism and quantum

00:07:57.220 --> 00:07:58.480
mechanics.

00:07:58.480 --> 00:08:02.650
And he presented a way
of thinking about this

00:08:02.650 --> 00:08:05.950
to understand the electric
force between two charges which

00:08:05.950 --> 00:08:08.740
had been understood
by Faraday and Maxwell

00:08:08.740 --> 00:08:10.360
in a slightly
different way-- a way

00:08:10.360 --> 00:08:13.600
we talk of by Feynman
diagrams, as we call them.

00:08:13.600 --> 00:08:16.690
But it's particularly
interesting.

00:08:16.690 --> 00:08:18.060
So this is an electron.

00:08:18.060 --> 00:08:19.860
And it repels another electron.

00:08:19.860 --> 00:08:24.670
And it does so by the exchange
of a particle-- a photon--

00:08:24.670 --> 00:08:26.560
the quantum of the
electromagnetic field.

00:08:26.560 --> 00:08:29.730
Electromagnetic waves come
in particles and photons

00:08:29.730 --> 00:08:31.240
of the individual [? quanta. ?]

00:08:31.240 --> 00:08:34.690
Now, what Feynman used
in developing this

00:08:34.690 --> 00:08:37.750
is a key aspect of
quantum mechanics, which

00:08:37.750 --> 00:08:40.299
is central to quantum
mechanics, which is really

00:08:40.299 --> 00:08:43.120
the same thing that's
used in Washington

00:08:43.120 --> 00:08:46.960
in corporate America, which
are now the same thing.

00:08:46.960 --> 00:08:50.960
If you can't see
it, anything goes.

00:08:50.960 --> 00:08:52.319
OK, that's basically it.

00:08:52.319 --> 00:08:54.610
And we'll learn more about
that with the investigations

00:08:54.610 --> 00:08:56.151
over the next year,
I certainly hope.

00:09:00.010 --> 00:09:02.856
So the idea is that this
electron emits this particle--

00:09:02.856 --> 00:09:03.730
this photon of light.

00:09:03.730 --> 00:09:05.600
But that's impossible.

00:09:05.600 --> 00:09:06.660
It's not allowed.

00:09:06.660 --> 00:09:09.490
The electron just sitting
there cannot emit a particle

00:09:09.490 --> 00:09:11.800
of light, because where
did the energy come from?

00:09:11.800 --> 00:09:14.610
If the photon carries energy,
where did the energy come from?

00:09:14.610 --> 00:09:17.200
The electron is still there
if it's an isolated electron.

00:09:17.200 --> 00:09:20.920
It can't emit a photon, because
that doesn't conserve energy.

00:09:20.920 --> 00:09:21.820
But that's OK.

00:09:21.820 --> 00:09:24.490
That's allowed by the
Heisenberg uncertainty

00:09:24.490 --> 00:09:27.450
principle, which is
responsible for that Washington

00:09:27.450 --> 00:09:28.360
rule I gave you.

00:09:28.360 --> 00:09:29.860
The Heisenberg
uncertainty principle

00:09:29.860 --> 00:09:32.990
says, if I measure a
system for a short time,

00:09:32.990 --> 00:09:35.650
then I can't know
its energy exactly.

00:09:35.650 --> 00:09:37.550
There's some uncertainty
in the energy.

00:09:37.550 --> 00:09:41.830
So if I emit this photon, and
it violates energy conservation

00:09:41.830 --> 00:09:43.550
that's allowed in
quantum mechanics,

00:09:43.550 --> 00:09:46.620
as long as the photon
disappears in such a short time

00:09:46.620 --> 00:09:47.620
that I can't measure it.

00:09:47.620 --> 00:09:50.180
It's just exactly
like embezzlement.

00:09:50.180 --> 00:09:51.820
OK?

00:09:51.820 --> 00:09:55.060
And I'm sure Google does
this every day at some level,

00:09:55.060 --> 00:09:57.250
because if you get the
money, and as you put it back

00:09:57.250 --> 00:10:00.590
before anyone notices, you can
do whatever you want with it.

00:10:00.590 --> 00:10:01.090
Right?

00:10:01.090 --> 00:10:02.890
And you know, there's
a lot of trading

00:10:02.890 --> 00:10:04.490
that goes on in that regard.

00:10:04.490 --> 00:10:05.840
So it's exactly the same.

00:10:05.840 --> 00:10:08.800
So the photon can violate
energy conservation here.

00:10:08.800 --> 00:10:11.170
As long as it disappears
before you can measure it,

00:10:11.170 --> 00:10:11.680
you're fine.

00:10:11.680 --> 00:10:14.440
And so the photons exchange,
and it produces that repulsion.

00:10:14.440 --> 00:10:17.620
Now the key point is the
photon has zero mass.

00:10:17.620 --> 00:10:18.610
It's massless.

00:10:18.610 --> 00:10:22.960
And that's essential to
make electromagnetism

00:10:22.960 --> 00:10:24.130
a long-range force.

00:10:24.130 --> 00:10:27.110
The electron here repels an
electron in Alpha Centauri.--

00:10:27.110 --> 00:10:29.470
OK-- or anywhere
in another galaxy.

00:10:29.470 --> 00:10:32.410
And the reason is, because
the photon is massless,

00:10:32.410 --> 00:10:36.452
it can carry an arbitrarily
small amount of energy.

00:10:36.452 --> 00:10:38.410
And if it can carry an
arbitrarily small amount

00:10:38.410 --> 00:10:41.380
of energy, then it can exist
for an arbitrarily long time

00:10:41.380 --> 00:10:43.709
before it has to disappear
without violating

00:10:43.709 --> 00:10:45.250
the Heisenberg
uncertainty principle.

00:10:45.250 --> 00:10:47.230
And if it can exist for
an arbitrary long time,

00:10:47.230 --> 00:10:51.230
it can travel from here to Alpha
Centauri before it's absorbed.

00:10:51.230 --> 00:10:52.660
So the fact that
electromagnetism

00:10:52.660 --> 00:10:57.040
is a long-range force is
uniquely related to the fact

00:10:57.040 --> 00:10:59.300
that the photon is
massless, in this picture.

00:10:59.300 --> 00:10:59.800
OK?

